Data Cleaning¶

Replace Object to Categorical data¶

For sake of faster computation, we chose to convert object types which are enumerations of string elements to categorical data, for which the computation is way faster in pandas.

In [8]:
def object_to_cat(col):
    """
        Returns col as type category if col is object else return object
    """
    if col.dtype == object:
        return col.astype('category')
    else:
        return col

    """
        Returns a (location string, google location data) tuple.

    # Please note that the dataset is based on Ames, IOWA data.

In [15]:
def get_latitude(neighborhood):
    return geocodedLocations_lnglat.get(neighborhood, (0., 0.))[0]
def get_longitude(neighborhood):
    return geocodedLocations_lnglat.get(neighborhood, (0.,0.))[1]

sellsCountHeatMap = (
    training_data[["Neighborhood", "Id"]]
        .groupby("Neighborhood")
        .agg("count")
).reset_index()

# Add latitude and longitude
sellsCountHeatMap["latitude"] = sellsCountHeatMap.apply(lambda x: get_latitude(x.Neighborhood) , axis=1)
sellsCountHeatMap["longitude"] = sellsCountHeatMap.apply(lambda x: get_longitude(x.Neighborhood), axis=1)

# Remove the not found locations
sellsCountHeatMap = sellsCountHeatMap[sellsCountHeatMap.latitude != 0]

Inequalities visualization¶

Let's describe those inequalities, digging more into the details:

In [21]:
categories_agg = {
    # Overall quality of the houses aggregated by mean
    "OverallQual":  "mean",
    
    # Proportion of the district that has Central air cond.
    "CentralAir":   lambda x: np.mean(x=="Y"), 
    
    # Mean area of the houses in a given neighborhood
    "GrLivArea":    "mean", 
    
    # Mean area of lot sizes
    "LotArea":      "mean",
    
    # Proportion of the district that has at least
    # a good looking house
    "ExterQual":    lambda x: np.mean(x.isin(["Ex", "Gd"])),
    
    # Mean area of pools (no pool = 0)
    "PoolArea":     lambda x: np.mean(x.fillna(0)),
}

categories = list(categories_agg)

inequalities_df = (training_data
                   
      # Keep only the selected locations
    [training_data.Neighborhood.isin(selected_locations)]
                   
      # Get only a few subset of relevant data
    [["Neighborhood"]+categories]
                   
      # Group and aggregate
    .groupby("Neighborhood")
                   
      # Aggregate functions
    .agg(categories_agg)
                   
      # Drop other neighborhoods
     .dropna()
                   
      # Normalize in order to spider plot
     .apply(lambda x: x/x.max())
)
In [22]:
from itertools import cycle
colors = cycle(["r", "g", "b"])

# Preprocess data to plot
values = np.hstack((inequalities_df.values, inequalities_df.values[:,[0]])).T
angles = [n / float(len(categories)) * 2 * np.pi for n in range(len(categories))]
angles += angles[:1]

# Then plot the data
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 7))

ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)
ax.plot(angles, values, "-o",linewidth=2, linestyle='solid')
ax.legend(selected_locations, prop={'size':12}, bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
for v in values.T:
    ax.fill(angles, v, color=next(colors), alpha=.1)

plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, color='purple', size=15)
plt.title("Inequalities visualization (stand. scale)", size=16, weight="bold")
plt.show()

Conclusion on spacial differentiation¶

The first thing that comes to mind when dealing with housing is probably where ? and you'll be probably right if you say that one of the main criteria in the price setting of a house or an appartment is its location. This is especialy true is the USA as shown in the following heatmap (Source) of San Francisco median home prices. The price range is huge (a log scale would almost be needed ...).

Multiple factors are leading to this analysis, including differents standards of living with regard to the districts (house/appartment/villa, area, build quality). Those criterias cumulate in order to estimate the overall price of the house, thus the neighborhood has no value by itself determining the price of houses, but it underlies several factors (including ones that the dataset may lack of).


Moreover, this analysis is made possible by the strong homogeneity of the factors found in each neighborhood.
We also found that the gradation of neighborhoods involves that all of the comfort creteria evolves positively when getting into higher standards area, as shown in the previous question. The least valuated areas are far behing the most valuated ones for all of the factors!


All of this leads us to distinguish spatially the analysis when dealing with housing. (for instance for the outliers analysis, for filling the Na values in the test set, and much more). The important point is that there are underlying latent factors in the spatial information and those are very important in the price setting as shown in the next part.


Funny fact: please note that even in the less valuated neighborhoods, homes have as much access to air conditionning as much more valuated ones. Welcome in America!

Determine the relationship between numerical features¶

We chose here to process the categorical data later and at first to analyse the numerical features in order to have a better understanding of the dataset.
We will see later that the non numerical data will be transformed to numerical data using dummy variables and that the indicator that we use in this section will also apply to those dummy variables, but the results are much less human-readable.

Mutual information¶

The mutual information measures the amount of information that is contained in each couple of variables. In that specific case it it very interesting to estimate the mutual information shared with the SalePrice parameter.


This is also more relevant than looking at the correlation which doesn't care of the linearity of the association of two variables whereas the correlation does. But the mutual information is also more difficult to calculate as we must have an idea of the the distribution of the variables. This is what is performed by scikit-learn that works with samples and calculates the MI from the cardinality of the generated sets.

$\begin{align} MI(U, V) &= E\left( ln\frac{p(u, v)}{p(u)p(v)} \right)\\ &= \sum_{i=1}^{|U|} \sum_{j=1}^{|V|} \frac{|U_i \cap V_j|}{N} \cdot log \left(\frac {N \cdot |U_i \cap V_j|} {|U_i| \cdot |V_j|} \right) \text{ (Using Sklearn sampling cardinality)} \end{align}$

Normalized MI:

$ NMI(U, V) = \frac {MI(U, V)} {\sqrt{|U| \cdot |V|}} $

In [25]:
from sklearn.metrics import normalized_mutual_info_score

def calc_MI(x, y):
    mi = normalized_mutual_info_score(x, y)
    return mi
In [26]:
cols = num_data.columns

mutual_num_data = pd.DataFrame(
    [[ calc_MI(num_data[i], num_data[j]) 
          for j in cols ] for i in cols],
    index=cols,
    columns=cols
)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
plt.title("Normalized mutual information coefficients")
sns.heatmap(mutual_num_data, mask=mask, cmap="Blues")
plt.show()

As exected, the Id of the sale is the indicator that contains the more information about the price. As it is a primary key for the price this is obvious, but it has no phyisical meaning and is not a feature of the data. Therefore we have to eliminate it. Thought, this draw the attention on the fact that mutual information doesn't search for linear correlation (for which the Id is not so much correlated to the price).


The most relevant features are therefore the ones that comes to mind when buying a house, namely those related to the surface and the spacial information (district).

Use categorical data for regression : introducing Dummy Variables¶

Categorical data can't be use as is for regression and therefore we have into transform them to numerical data. One way to perform that is used to do that is dummy variables. The principle is quite simple: for a categorical type that includes n elements $\{e_1, ..., e_n \}$, we need $n-1$ dummy variable to represent a type (in the space $\{0, 1\}^{n-1}$). The projection from from the categorical space $C$ to the numerical space is computed as follows:

$$ \begin{align} f : \hspace{1cm} e_1 &\longrightarrow (\delta_{(1, 1)}, \dots, \delta_{(1, n-1)})\\ \dots \\ e_i &\longrightarrow (\delta_{(i, 1)}, \dots, \delta_{(i, i)}, \dots, \delta_{(i, n-1)})\\ \dots \\ e_{n-1} &\longrightarrow (\delta_{(n-1, 1)}, \dots, \delta_{(n-1, n-1)})\\ e_{n} &\longrightarrow (\delta_{(n, 1)}, \dots, \delta_{(n, n-1)}) \hspace{1cm} \text{(which is null)}\\ \end{align} $$ where $\delta{(i, j)}$ is the kronecker symbol.

Outliers¶

Here we chose to work district by district as it happens in real life, when real estates are evaluating a house, the neighborhood is probably one of the best criteria and the price setting is made according to the previous prices set in the same area for equivalent houses (one fact about district is that in the same area, chances are very high that the houses have the same characteristics, especialy in the US).


Thus, we chose to remove the outlier prices in each neighborhood. In all the nieghborhoods we have seen that the prices distribution is gaussian and therefore removing the outliers makes sense.

Normalization/Standardization¶

Why normalizing/standardizing?¶

The process of normalization/standardization is usefull when value ranges of different features are very different. This avoids for the training algorithm to overweight a priori some features (the ones that have the greatest values). It is therefore very important to normalize/standardize each of the features for the estimator not to be biaised.

Normalization vs Standardization¶

Normalization rescales the values into a range of $\left[0,1\right]$. This doesn't preserve the characteristics of gaussian distributions are the outliers are lost. But this have the advantage of having positive values only. $$X_{normalized}=\frac{XX_{min}}{X_{max}X_{min}}$$
Standardization rescales data to have a mean ($\mu$) of 0 and standard deviation ($\sigma$) of 1. It preserves the gaussian characteristics of the model and not all the values are positive. $$X_{standardized}=\frac{X\mu}{\sigma}$$

In our specific case, as we deal with gaussian processes (we have seen that the prices follows a Gauss function with respect of almost every important factor). Furthermore, when using test data, the scaler has alrady been computed on the training data, and using a normalization would include a risk of having values greater that one (if the max of a feature in the test data is greater than the max for this feature in the training data).


Therefore we chose to standardize our data.

Metrics¶

Note on the metrics

As the data is standardized the Mean Absolute error and the Mean Square error are computed on the standardized data dans therefore with respect to the variance and the mean of the dataset. As a reminder, the scaling of the y data is computed as follows: $y_{standard} = \frac{y - mean(y)}{std(y)}$.


The metric that is suggested is the folloving one:

$$ \begin{align} error_{RMSE(log)}(\hat{y}, y) &= \sqrt{\sum_i \left[log\left(\hat{y}_i\right) - log\left(y_i\right)\right]^2}\\ &= \sqrt{\sum_i \left[log\left(\frac{\hat{y}_i}{y_i}\right)\right]^2} \end{align} $$


Therefore, by homogeneity,

$$ \begin{align} dim \left[\frac{\hat{y}}{y}\right] &= dim \left[exp\left(error_{RMSE(log)}\left(\hat{y}, y\right)\right)\right] \end{align} $$


Then to have an approcimation of the error rate on each house price:

$$ \begin{align} error_{rate}\left(\hat{y}, y\right) &= \left[e^{error_{RMSE(log)}\left(\hat{y}, y\right)}\right] - 1\\ &= exp\left(\sqrt{\sum_i \left[log\left(\frac{\hat{y}_i}{y_i}\right)\right]^2}\right) - 1 \end{align} $$


For instance, an error of 0.0150 with this metric, would correspond to a precision of $exp(0.015) - 1 = 1,51\%$ on the estimated price.


This led us to create a fourth metric which will be computed as the error rate above, based on the RMSE(log). We call it Precision in this document.

In [41]:
from sklearn.metrics import get_scorer, make_scorer

def MeanAbsErr(*args, **kwargs):
    """
        Returns the average absolute error.
        Note that the inputs have to be standardized!
        The arguments are the seame as for sklearn 'neg_mean_absolute_error'
    """
    NegMeanAbsoluteError = get_scorer('neg_mean_absolute_error')
    return -NegMeanAbsoluteError(*args, **kwargs)

def MeanSqrErr(*args, **kwargs):
    """
        Returns the average square error.
        Note that the inputs have to be standardized!
        The arguments are the seame as for sklearn 'neg_mean_squared_error'
    """
    NegMeanSquareError = get_scorer("neg_mean_squared_error")
    return -NegMeanSquareError(*args, **kwargs)

def logRMSE_score(y_true, y_pred, *args):
    """
        Returns the RMSE between the logarithm of the predicted value 
        and the logarithm of the observed sales price.  
        
        Note that this metric destandardized the price
    """
    return np.sqrt(np.mean(
        # Please note that the minus operator is more accurate in python 
        # than the division operator when dealing with float
        np.log(inverse_y(y_pred))
        -
        np.log(inverse_y(y_true))
    )**2)

def precision_score(y_true, y_pred, *args):
    """
        Returns the precision score as described above.
        Returns a percentage
        
        Note that this metric denormalize the price
    """
    return 100*(np.exp(logRMSE_score(y_true, y_pred, *args))-1)

logRMSE = make_scorer(logRMSE_score)
precision = make_scorer(precision_score)

metrics_list = [{"name":"Mean Absolute Error (Standard)",  "function":MeanAbsErr},
                {"name":"Mean Square Error (Standard)",    "function":MeanSqrErr},
                {"name":"RMSE (log)",                  "function":logRMSE},
                {"name":"Precision (%)",               "function":precision},]

Test function¶

In [43]:
from sklearn.cross_validation import KFold, cross_val_score
from itertools import product as cart_product



def predict_and_test_cv(
    # training data
    X, Y, 
    # estimation functions (see sklearn doc)
    estimators_list, 
    # metric functions
    metrics_list, 
    # number of folds used in k-fold cross-validation
    folds_nb=5):
    
    """
        Input data structures:
        - estimators_list: [{"name":name estimator 1", "function":estimator_function_1}, 
                            {...}, 
                            ...]
        - metrics_list: [{"name""name metric 1", "function":metric_function_1}, 
                         {...}, 
                         ...]
                         
        Uses cross validation as validation method
    """
    
    def predict_and_score_one(row):  
        """
            To apply on results dataframe
        """
        return np.mean(cross_val_score(
            row.Estimator["function"],
            X, Y,
            cv=cv, 
            scoring=row.Metric["function"]
        ))
    
    # Use cross validation to avoid overfitting
    cv = KFold(X.shape[0], folds_nb, shuffle=True, random_state=33)
    
    params = pd.DataFrame(
        list(cart_product(estimators_list, metrics_list)),
        columns=["Estimator", "Metric"]
    )
    
    params["Score"] = params.apply(predict_and_score_one, axis=1)
    params[["Estimator", "Metric"]] = \
        params[["Estimator", "Metric"]].applymap(lambda x: x["name"])
    params.set_index(["Estimator", "Metric"], inplace=True)
    return pd.DataFrame(params)

def predict_and_plot_cv(*args, **kwargs):
    """
        Same args as for predict_and_test
    """
    prediction_result = predict_and_test_cv(*args, **kwargs)
    
    # Plot the result
    axs = prediction_result\
        .reset_index()\
        .pivot("Estimator", "Metric", "Score")\
        .plot.bar(subplots=True, figsize=(15, 5), layout=(1, 4))
    plt.suptitle("Errors (Normalized training data)")
    for ax in axs.reshape(-1):
        ax.legend(fancybox=True, shadow=True)
    plt.show()
    
    # Return the prediction results 
    return prediction_result

Test data processing¶

In [53]:
from sklearn.base import clone

def predict_and_test(
    # training data
    X_train, Y_train,
    # test data
    X_test,
    # estimation functions (see sklearn doc)
    estimator):
    
    # Do not use the original estimator to not bias its weights
    estimator = clone(estimator)
    
    # Then fit and predict
    estimator.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    X_test["SalePrice"] = estimator.predict(X_test)
    
    return X_test
